<p>There are three possible configurations between a course master and section(s), as illustrated below.</p>
<h2>A Master With a Single Section Linked to It</h2>
<p><img alt="Box labeled master with an arrow to a single box labeled section" height="96" src="Images/academic-technology-services/FTC/PDP-graphic-config1-1.jpg" style="float: left;" width="331" />This configuration is appropriate if you teach a single section of a course.</p>
<p><a href="x69032.xml">Advantages and cautions associated with this configuration</a></p>
<p></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p></p>
<h2>A Master With Multiple Sections Linked to It; Sections are S<em>eparated<strong><br /></strong></em></h2>
<p><img alt="Box labeled master with two arrows leading to two separate boxes labeled section." height="157" src="Images/academic-technology-services/FTC/PDP-Graphic-config-2.jpg" style="float: left;" width="335" /></p>
<p></p>
<p><strong><em></em></strong>This configuration <strong></strong>is appropriate if you teach multiple sections of the same course, and you prefer to manage each class of students separately.</p>
<p><a href="x69181.xml">Advantages and cautions associated with this configuration</a></p>
<p></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<h2>A Master with Multiple Sections Linked to It; Sections are C<em>ombined</em><strong><em><br /></em></strong></h2>
<p><em><strong></strong></em><strong> <img alt="Box labeled master with a single arrow leading to two boxes that have been merged together that are each labeled section." height="157" src="Images/academic-technology-services/FTC/PDP-graphic-config3.jpg" style="float: left;" width="335" /></strong></p>
<p></p>
<p><strong><em></em></strong><em><strong></strong></em>This configuration is appropriate if you teach multiple sections of the same course, and you prefer to manage the classes of students collectively.<br /><br /> <a href="x69181.xml">Advantages and cautions associated with this configuration</a><br /><br /></p>
<p></p>
<p><em>&nbsp;</em></p>
